//music
Nokia's famous ringtone is plagiarized, but it didn't break the law.
The passage that became the first musical ringtone on cell phones was originally called Grande valse, but was later given the name Nokia tune.
The story goes that in 1993, Nokia took an extract from the guitar composition Grande Valse, written in 1902 by the then famous Spanish composer Francisco Tarrega.
They did not thereby break the law, because European law allows music to be made available to the public 70 years after the composer's death.
Is Nokia's famous ringtone plagiarized?

And what about the "DJ era" when you could make your own music on your Nokia?
Во времена, когда еще не было возможности скачивать мп3 песни, у Nokia был свой формат кода, который переводил текст в мелодию. Такой формат известен как RTTTL (Ring Tone Text Transfer Language).
By placing notes and pauses in the right order, you could play any popular melody or even create your own unique ringtone.
However, you could keep only 7 of these ringtones on your phone. But at least you could share your creation with your friends!
You could make your own music on Nokia!

Afterward, there were dozens of Blockade clones , one of which has inspired Taneli Armanto, the creator of Snake at Nokia.
It all started with Blockade, a two-player arcade game developed in 1976 by Gremlin Interactive, a video game company.
By the way, the Snake wasn't original either, did you know that?
So the original Snake appeared in 1997. In the same year, the company released the first phone with this game - Nokia 6110.
